{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Emacs-Errors","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Emacs Errors"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Emacs Lisp is a dynamically typed language, the majority of input validation and type conformance checks end up being errors. It is a normal state of things. Runtime errors in Lisp doesn’t have a stigma to them like in some other languages, especially because the user can literally call functions all the time."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"EmacsSwiftModule"},{"type":"text","text":", we surface Lisp runtime errors as Swift exceptions. And in the vast majority of the cases users should just re-throw errors back to the user. Again, this is normal, especially if it happens in a user-facing function. Any interaction with "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"},{"type":"text","text":" can potentially throw. You only handle these errors yourself if you actually expect a very specific error as a possibility and have a backup plan."}]},{"anchor":"Swift-Errors","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Swift Errors"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"At the same time, Swift code exceptions are also fine and will be translated into Emacs error signals. You probably want to handle a bigger portion of this kind of errors, but if you won’t, nothing bad will happen. If it won’t crash Emacs, it’s not critical."}]},{"style":"important","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you choose to disable error propagation via "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"try!"},{"type":"text","text":", and do get an exception, it will crash Emacs. Swift runtime errors are critical."}]}],"type":"aside","name":"Important"},{"anchor":"User-Interruptions","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"User Interruptions"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If your code introduces a long-running Lisp function, you should check from time to time if the user interrupted it by pressing "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"C-g"},{"type":"text","text":" (or similar). In this situation, it is recommended to quit any work as soon as possible. You can check it via "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment\/interrupted()"},{"type":"text","text":" method. If you work with environment, any call to it will throw "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/interrupted"},{"type":"text","text":", when in this state."}]},{"anchor":"Lifetime-Violations","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Lifetime Violations"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"},{"type":"text","text":" checks for lifetime and thread model consistency and throws "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/lifetimeViolation"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/threadModelViolation"},{"type":"text","text":". Check "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes"},{"type":"text","text":" for more details."}]}]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"sections":[],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/errorhandling"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Handling Lisp errors on Swift side and vice versa."}],"kind":"article","metadata":{"roleHeading":"Article","title":"Error Handling","role":"article","modules":[{"name":"EmacsSwiftModule"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule"]]},"seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Getting started","identifiers":["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions"],"generated":true}],"references":{"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningAModule":{"role":"article","title":"Defining a module","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining a new Emacs module from Swift."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","kind":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/definingamodule"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningLispFunctions":{"role":"article","title":"Defining Lisp Functions","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining Emacs Lisp functions directly from Swift."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","kind":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/defininglispfunctions"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/TypeConversions":{"role":"article","title":"Type conversions","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Converting Swift values into Lisp values and vice versa."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","kind":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/typeconversions"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment/interrupted()":{"role":"symbol","title":"interrupted()","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"func"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"interrupted"},{"kind":"text","text":"() -> "},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"Bool","preciseIdentifier":"s:Sb"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Checks whether the user interrupted execution of the current function."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment\/interrupted()","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment\/interrupted()"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/CallingLispFunctions":{"role":"article","title":"Calling Lisp Functions","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calling Lisp functions from your Swift code."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","kind":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/callinglispfunctions"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/threadModelViolation":{"role":"symbol","title":"EmacsError.threadModelViolation","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"threadModelViolation"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Using "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"},{"type":"text","text":" in a different thread than issued it."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/threadModelViolation","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/threadmodelviolation"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/lifetimeViolation":{"role":"symbol","title":"EmacsError.lifetimeViolation","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"lifetimeViolation"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Using "},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"},{"type":"text","text":" outside of its scope."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/lifetimeViolation","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/lifetimeviolation"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment":{"role":"symbol","title":"Environment","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"Environment"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Environment is the interaction point with Emacs. If you want to do anything on the Emacs side, you need to have an Environment."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"Environment"}],"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError/interrupted":{"role":"symbol","title":"EmacsError.interrupted","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"case"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"interrupted"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Emacs user interruption (C-g)."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError\/interrupted","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror\/interrupted"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Lifetimes":{"role":"article","title":"Lifetimes","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Emacs internals lifetimes."}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","kind":"article","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/lifetimes"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule":{"role":"collection","title":"EmacsSwiftModule","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A Swift library to write Emacs plugins in Swift!"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftMo